prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: ISM Mass Estimates for z = 2-3 Starforming Galaxies using 345 Ghz dust continuum
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: We will measure the long wavelength dust continuum from a sample starforming galaxies at z = 2-3 with stellar mass > 2x10^10 msun. This emission on the Rayleigh-Jeans tail of the SED will be optically thin and the detected flux is directly proportioanl to the dust mass and hence total ISM mass.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We request a continuum sensitivity in the 3 science goals such that we will achieve ~3 sigma detection of the expected dust continuum in Band 7 assuming the fiducial ISM mass of 20 billion solar masses. (This mass is twice the fiducial value used to generate Fig. 2-left.) The requested rms sensitivities are 0.15mJy (Band 7), the same as for the Cycle 2 program. The major goal of this project is to determine the total fluxes for each of the sample galaxies; thus high resolution is not required although in a few cases the imaging may reveal multiple source components or extension to ~1 arcsec. There are no strong sources in the COSMOS field. There are no scheduling-time constraints.

We are making a simple continuum measurement with 3.8 GHz in each sideband but would like to retain low resolution spectral channels for possible search for sernedipity emission lines. If this causes a data rate issue, it is viable to go to a single continuum measurement for each spectral band.
We are focussing on total flux measurements as in our Cycle 2 project. The sources should be ~1 arcsec in size so we may see a little structure or see multiple sources in the FOV.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to extend our extremely successful program of measuring interstellar (ISM) masses in high-z galaxies at the peak of cosmic star formation and active galactic nuclei (AGN). Our technique uses optically thin dust emission as a proxy for the ISM gas mass -- calibrated using Planck observations of the Milky Way, nearby galaxies and SMGs at z ~ 2. The sensitivity and resolution of ALMA make the technique very quick and reliable (avoiding issues of CO conversion factors). In Cycle 2, we found very large increases in the ISM masses as one goes above the main sequence and at higher z. Confirmation of this important result requires observations of a larger and IR-complete sample. We propose 368 galaxies in the redshift ranges z = 1-2, 2-3 and 3-5 (43% with spectroscopic redshifts). All have good detections with Herschel, providing a reliable accounting of the dust-obscured star formation and AGN. These extensive samples will be used to map the evolution of ISM mass as a function of redshift, galactic stellar mass, and star formation rate relative to the main sequence. 59 of the galaxies have X-ray AGN to be compared with non-AGN samples.
